data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change.

**What happened:** In C# 14, new built-in span conversions mean `array.Contains(num)` now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. `MemoryExtensions.Contains` is **not representable in expression trees**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

**How to fix:** Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by treating the array as `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<T>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these ensures the expression tree references the `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which is expression-treeâ€“compatible.
